data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement.

## Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes thread from `WaitOne()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Timeout enforcement — kills thread if `Join` times out |
| `while (true)` loop | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop — no exit condition |

Both `Thread.Interrupt()` (SYSLIB0046) and `Thread.Abort()` (SYSLIB0006/PlatformNotSupportedException) must be replaced.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts!.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wait for either a new event OR cancellation — replaces
            // Thread.Interrupt() which was used to wake from WaitOne().
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
                new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle });

            if (signaled == 1) // cancellation token was signaled
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items — the original code had a bug where
            // multiple Enqueue() calls between WaitOne() returns would
            // only dequeue one item per signal.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null || _thread == null)
            return;

        // Signal cooperative cancellation — replaces both
        // Thread.Interrupt() and Thread.Abort().
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread.Join(5000);

        // If the thread is still alive after 5s, there is no safe
        // equivalent to Thread.Abort(). Log/alert — the thread is
        // stuck in uncooperative code.
        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes

1. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → `CancellationToken.WaitHandle`** — `WaitHandle.WaitAny` wakes the thread from its blocking `WaitOne` when the token is cancelled. No exception is thrown; the thread simply resumes and checks the index.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → removed** — There is **no equivalent** in .NET 8. `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. After `_cts.Cancel()` + `Join(5000)`, if the thread is still alive, you must accept it or move the work to a child `Process` that you can `Process.Kill()`.

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The loop cooperatively checks for cancellation on each iteration.

4. **Bug fix: queue drain** — The original only dequeued one item per signal. If `Enqueue` was called twice before the loop iterated, the second item was stuck until a third enqueue. The inner `while` loop now drains all pending items.

## Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **`Handle()` blocks forever** | If `Handle()` never returns, cancellation can't take effect — it's cooperative. Add `token` as a parameter to `Handle()` and check it inside long operations. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` not disposed** | `CTS` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always dispose in `Stop()` or via `using`. |
| **No fallback for stuck threads** | .NET 8 cannot forcibly kill a thread. If `Handle()` calls uncooperative code (e.g., native blocking I/O), move it to a child process so you can call `Process.Kill()`. |
| **Race between `Reset()` and `Enqueue()`** | If `Enqueue()` calls `Set()` between `WaitAny` returning and `Reset()`, the signal is lost. The drain loop mitigates this — the item is already in the queue and will be processed. A `ManualResetEventSlim` or `AutoResetEvent` can further tighten this. |

## Optional Modern Alternative

For new .NET 8 code, consider replacing the entire manual thread + queue + lock pattern with `Channel<T>`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _worker;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts!.Cancel();
        if (_worker != null)
            await _worker.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

This eliminates the manual `ManualResetEvent`, `lock`, `Queue`, and `Thread` entirely. `Channel<T>` handles all synchronization internally and is cancellation-aware out of the box.
